<subSubSection id="C3266529FFB8FFADFF0CFA8BD931FA29" pageId="6" pageNumber="331" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFB8FFADFF0CFA8BD931FA29" blockId="6.[151,1437,1244,1739]" pageId="6" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFB8FFADFF0CFA8BD903FABA" bold="true" box="[199,322,1317,1343]" pageId="6" pageNumber="331">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity id="4CC49B47FFB8FFADFE68FA8BDA6EFABA" box="[419,559,1317,1343]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="6" pageNumber="331" unit="mm" value="1.2" valueMax="1.3" valueMin="1.1">1.1–1.3 mm</quantity>
; color dark reddish brown to black; eyes separated above by 2.9–3.1 × their width; female frons concave, with a broad projecting tuft of setae along the dorsal margin of impression; scapus with dense tuft of plumose setae longer than the club; elytral disc and declivity lightly rugose (females) to distinctly granulated (males).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266529FFB8FFADFF0CFA1BDAC2F9DA" pageId="6" pageNumber="331" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFB8FFADFF0CFA1BDA38F992" blockId="6.[151,1437,1244,1739]" pageId="6" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFB8FFADFF0CFA1BD9B5FA4A" bold="true" box="[199,500,1461,1487]" pageId="6" pageNumber="331">Distribution and biology.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F32B7632FFB8FFADFE37FA1BDAC4FA4A" box="[508,645,1461,1487]" name="Madagascar" pageId="6" pageNumber="331">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
. Previously only known from the 
<typeStatus id="54878800FFB8FFADFBC2FA1BDC78FA4A" box="[1033,1081,1461,1487]" pageId="6" pageNumber="331">type</typeStatus>
locality where it was dissected from 
<quantity id="4CC49B47FFB8FFADFF1FFA77D966FA76" box="[212,295,1497,1524]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="331" unit="cm" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5 cm</quantity>
thick branches of an unknown host plant (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFB8FFADFCCAFA77DBD3FA76" author="Schedl, K. E." box="[769,914,1497,1523]" pageId="6" pageNumber="331" pagination="1 - 326" refId="ref10622" refString="Schedl, K. E. (1977) Die Scolytidae und Platypodidae Madagaskars und einiger naheliegender Inselgruppen. Mitteilungen der Forstlichen Bundes-Versuchsanstalt Wien, 119, 1 - 326." type="journal article" year="1977">Schedl 1977</bibRefCitation>
). Two females per male made longitudinal egg tunnels, presumably in opposite directions.
</paragraph>
